 Geoderma, 35 (1985) 91-107  91  Elsevier Science Publishers B.V., Amsterdam - Printed in The Netherlands    SHAPES OF AGGREGATES FROM TILLED LAYERS OF SOME DUTCH  AND AUSTRALIAN SOILS    A.R. DEXTER    Department of Soil Science, Waite Agricultural Research Institute, The University of  Adelaide, Glen Osmond, South Australia 5064 (Australia)    (Received August 21, 1984; accepted after revision February 14, 1985)    ABSTRACT    Dexter, A.R., 1985. Shapes of aggregates from tilled layers of some Dutch and Australian  soils. Geoderma, 35: 91-107.     Five different methods were used to study the shapes of soil aggregates oriented in their planes of maximum projection. A measure of roundness was found to be relatively insensitive to shape features. The shortest aspect ratio (the ratio of the shortest to the longest diameters through the centroid) was found to be most sensitive of the "single value" shape measures. More comprehensive shape information was given by values of the radius spectra and the curvature spectra. The curvature spectra method seems to be slightly more sensitive than the radius spectra method and can also be applied to reentrant particles.   Generally it was found that aggregates are less round with increasing clay content and decreasing organic matter content. There was also a hint that aggregates of the Dutch soils may become less round with increasing age since their reclamation. The Australian soil aggregates were slightly rounder than the Dutch aggregates.    INTRODUCTION     The shape of soil aggregates is of interest because it can yield clues to the mechanisms of aggregate formation. Shape also influences a number of important soil physical properties including packing density or porosity and the relationship between aggregate crushing force and the tensile strength of the aggregate material. This latter problem was encountered by Dexter and Kroesbergen (1985).   Aggregate shape is usually considered in descriptive categories such as "rounded", "sub-rounded", "angular", "blocky", etc. Comparison of actual aggregates with pictures of standard shapes of particles enables the shapes of the aggregates to be put into the appropriate categories. Often, the standard shapes have been put into their categories on the basis of some quantitative criteria such as that of Wadell (1935). Examples of charts of standard shapes are those of Powers (1953) and of Krumbein and Sloss (1963) which was also used by Morse et al. (1982).    0016-7061/85/$03.301985 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V.  92     Several simple measures of particle shape have been devised and used. Cox (1927) defined roundness, R, to be the ratio of the projected area, A, of the particle to the area of a circle having the same perimeter, P:    R = 47/P2  (1)    This gives R = 1 for a sphere and R = 0 for a thin needle.   Another simple measure is the "aspect ratio" of a particle which is the ratio of the longest: intermediate: shortest axis lengths, x:y:z. These may be rendered dimensionless by dividing by the longest axis length to give l:xly: zlx. Using this method, Braunack et al. (1979) obtained mean aspect ratios for aggregates of several normally swelling soils of 1:0.73:0.50 at -153 MPa matric water potential and 1:0.87:0.70 at -100 kPa matric water potential. The reason for these apparent differences of shape with water potential remains unclear. For three Dutch soils, Dexter et al. (1984) reported aspect ratios around 1:0.78:0.65. For a soil of the Winton series from Penicuick, Scotland an aspect ratio of 1:0.75:0.60 has been found (S.T. Willatt, personal communication, 1984). The above aspect ratios are close to l:q:q2. This will be discussed later.   The advent of automatic scanning devices and computers has made particle shape measurements easier to make and has enabled more complex mathematical analysis of particle shapes to be done (e.g., Beddow and Meloy, 1980). The most commonly used of these methods is to perform a Fourier analysis of