aggregate, only the coordinates (x,y) of the perimeter were stored. This was done as follows.   Firstly, a quick scan was done along every tenth line and row of the picture so that the approximate centre of the aggregate could be determined. Then a pair of diagonal lines at + zr /4 and -7r /4 were generated through this point as shown in Fig.5. Scanning was then done along every line or column within each quadrant, and the coordinates of the edge of the particle were stored. About 500-600 coordinate pairs (x,y) were stored for each particle in this way.    Fig.5. Directions of scanning in four quadrants defined by two diagonal lines through the approximate centre of a photograph of an aggregate.  98     The above method was used because it is simple and gives fairly uniformly spaced data points, because it works with rather irregular images, and because it is faster than scanning the whole picture. Faster but more complex edge-following algorithms could have been applied.   From the coordinates of the edges, the centroid, area and perimeter of the aggregate image were calculated. This enabled values of the roundness, R, from eq. 1 to be determined. Two types of aspect ratios were calculated both of which are based on the maximum diameter, Dmax, of an aggregate which passes through the centroid. The right-angled aspect ratio, ARr, is the ratio of Dr to Dmax where Dr is the diameter through the centroid at right-angles to Dm ax    ARr =Dr/Dm ax  (12)    The shortest aspect ratio, AR,, is the ratio of the shortest diameter, Ds, which passes through the centroid, to Dmax    AR, =Ds/Dmax  (13)     For calculation of the Fourier spectrum of the radius using eqs. 2--7, the scanned points along the aggregate perimeter were linearly interpolated to give an arbitrary number (N = 128) of points spaced at equal angles (0 = 21r/128 radians) about the centroid.   For calculation of the curvature spectrum of the perimeter using eqs. 8-11 the scanned points along the perimeter were linearly interpolated to give an arbitrary number (N = 128) of points equally spaced in distance along the perimeter.    RESULTS    Cox's measure o f roundness     For the standard shapes shown in Fig.3, the roundness values are given by:    R =  0.463 + 0.122X + 0.325Y, (14)   (.027) (.028) (0.035)    where X and Y are the "roundness" and "sphericity" values of Krumbein and Sloss (1963) as shown in Fig.3.   For the Dutch aggregates, roundness values are given in Table II. The best correlation is between these and the clay (&lt; 2 pm) content values given in Table I. This gives    R = 0.740 - 0.0017 (clay)  (15)   (.017) (.0006)    which shows that the aggregates of the soils with higher clay contents are less round than those with lower clay contents.  99    TABLE II    Values of Cox's measure of roundness, R, and of the right-angle, ARr, and shortest, ARs, aspect ratios (figures in parentheses are standard errors)  Soil Roundness (R) Aspect ratios    ARr ARS    Dutch aggregates  D1 0.722 (0.009) 0.744 (0.019) 0.685 (0.016)  D2 0.702 (0.008) 0.681 (0.044) 0.648 (0.021)  D3 0.708 (0.010) 0.760 (0.027) 0.686 (0.021)  D4 0.716 (0.009) 0.739 (0.021) 0.668 (0.015)  D5 0.659 (0.011) 0.720 (0.026) 0.645 (0.025)  D6 0.679 (0.010) 0.679 (0.022) 0.633 (0.019)  D7 0.652 (0.013) 0.702 (0.046) 0.659 (0.027)  D8 0.700 (0.011) 0.772 (0.020) 0.728 (0.018)    Australian aggregates  A1 0.695 (0.010) 0.766 (0.020) 0.713 (0.016)  A2 0.673 (0.014) 0.712 (0.028) 0.656 (0.024)  A3 0.708 (0.012) 0.822 (0.028) 0.752 (0.021)  A4 0.713 (0.006) 0.734 (0.025) 0.696 (0.020)  A5 0.722 (0.010) 0.757 (0.026) 0.706 (0.021)    For the Australian aggregates, the mean value of roundness is  R = 0.702(.005) (16)  with no significant effect of organic matter content.    Aspect ratios    Aspect ratios of the standard shapes are given approximately by:  ARr = 0.172 + 0.770Y (17)   (0.055) (0.068)  and  AR, = 0.202 + 0.658Y (18)   (0.038) (0.050)  For the Dutch aggregates, aspect ratios are given in Table