sidered in terms of a simple model of aggregate fragmentation. Soil aggregates are likely to be most susceptible to breaking by bending stresses applied to their longest axes. It can be readily shown that if small aggregates are formed by the breaking in half of larger aggregates along their longest axes, and if aggregate shape is independent of aggregate size, then the aggregate aspect ratios must be:    l:q:q`  (29)    where q = (0.5)'3 = 0.794. This value is very similar to that which has been observed with several different soil types, although this does not mean that this is the only, or even the principal, mechanism of aggregate formation.   The values of q reported previously are directly comparable with the values of the right-angled aspect ratio, AR,, reported here. For the Dutch soil samples D1, D4 and D6, the new results obtained by scanning and computation are the same to within experimental error as the previous results (Dexter et al.,1984) obtained by measurement with calipers.   The results for the standard shapes of Krumbein and Sloss (1963) shown in Fig.5 are summarized in eqs. 14, 17, 18, 23 and 26. The lack of sensitivity of the aspect ratios to "roundness", X, in eqs. 17 and 18 was as expected and illustrates well the deficiency of simple aspect ratio measurements. There were not smooth trends in the spectra C(m) and S(k) with increasing m or k because of the rather arbitrary nature of the standard shapes and because there was only one example of a shape available for each combination of X and Y. The values are given here in full, however, as they are likely to be useful as a check in future studies.   The Dutch aggregates exhibited a decreasing roundness with increasing clay content (eq. 15) and this was consistent with the decreasing aspect ratios with increasing clay content (eqs. 19, 20). This is also consistent with the positive signs of the coefficients, b2, of eq. 24 given in Table IV, and the coefficients, bs, of eq. 27 given in Table VII. The aspect ratios of the Dutch aggregates are positively correlated with soil organic matter content (eqs. 19, 20) and this is consistent with the generally negative signs of the coefficients, c2, of eq. 24 given in Table IV, and of the coefficients, cs, of eq. 27 given in Table VII. There is, however, a strong positive correlation between clay content and organic matter content in these Dutch soils (Dexter et al., 1984). The apparent slight negative correlation between age of the soil since reclamation and aspect ratios (eqs. 19, 20) is consistent  106    with the slight tendency towards positive coefficients, d2, in eq. 24 and Table IV may indicate a small trend of increasing angularity of aggregates with age. Increased experimental replication would be necessary before a definite statement about this could be made.   With the Australian aggregates, the only variable considered was different organic matter contents resulting from a history of different crop rotations. Eqs. 21 and 22 show a slight increase in aspect ratios with increasing organic matter content. This is consistent with the generally negative coefficients b3 of eq. 25 given in Table V and bb of eq. 28 given in Table VIII.   The reason for the difference in shape between the Dutch and Australian aggregates remains unknown. The similarity of the trend of aggregate shape with increasing organic matter content in the samples from the two countries suggests that a similar mechanism may be responsible.   Of the different methods, the measure of roundness, R, was the worst because it was the least sensitive. The shortest aspect ratio, AR, was better than the right-angled aspect ratio, ARr, because it gave smaller relative standard errors. The radius spectra method came nearer to showing a trend of shape with age than did the curvature spectra method. The curvature spectra method clearly distinguished between the Dutch samples with high and lower clay contents which the radius spectra method did not. The curvature spectra method can be applied to re-entrant particles, whereas the radius spectra method cannot.   Future studies should use the shortest aspect ratio if quick, simple measurements are needed and possibly the curvature spectra method for more detailed studies especially where re-entrant particles are involved.   All of this work has been based on two-dimensional profiles or outlines of particles, whereas any complete description of particle shape would need to be three-dimensional. Tilmann (1973) concluded from a study of 50 sand-sized quartz grains that the shape information carried by the grains when in their orientation of maximum projected area does not differ significantly from the shape information carried by such grains in other orientations. Whether this is true or not for soil aggregates is not yet known. The plane of maximum projected area should be used in future studies.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS     This work was supported by the Wheat Industry Research Council of Australia. Mr. B. Kroesbergen of the Tillage Laboratory of the Agricultural University Wageningen, The Netherlands photographed the Dutch aggregates and Mr. B. Palk photographed the Australian aggregates. Mr. P. Brown assisted with the scanning and the computing. W.H. Freeman &amp; Co. of New York are thanked for permission to reproduce Figure 3.  107    REFERENCES    Beddow, J.K. and Meloy, T.P., 1980. Advanced Particulate Morphology. CRC Press, Boca Raton.  Braunack, M.V., Hewitt, J.S. and Dexter, A.R., 1979. Brittle fracture of soil aggregates and the compaction of aggregate beds. J. Soil Sci., 30: 653-667.  Cheng, D.C-H. and Sutton, H.M., 1971. Absolute determination of particle size and shape. Nature (Physical Science), 232: 192-193.  Cox, E.P., 1927. A method for assigning numerical and percentage values to the degree of roundness. J. Palaeontol., 1: 179-183.  Davis, P.F. and Dexter, A.R., 1972. Two methods for quantitative description of soil particle shape. J. Soil Sci., 23: 448-45